The white-naped tit was formerly one of the many species in the genus ''[[Parus]]'' but was moved to ''[[Machlolophus]]'' after a [[molecular phylogenetic]] analysis published in 2013 showed that the members of the new genus formed a distinct [[clade]].<ref name=paridae2013>{{ cite journal | last1=Johansson  | first1=U.S. | last2=Ekman | first2=J. | last3=Bowie | first3=R.C.K. | last4=Halvarsson | first4=P. | last5=Ohlson | first5=J.I. | last6=Price | first6=T.D. | last7=Ericson | first7=P.G.P. | year=2013 | title=A complete multilocus species phylogeny of the tits and chickadees (Aves: Paridae) | journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution | volume=69 | issue=3 | pages=852–860 | doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2013.06.019 | pmid=23831453}}</ref><ref name=ioc>{{cite web| editor1-last=Gill | editor1-first=Frank | editor2-last=Donsker | editor2-first=David | title=Waxwings and their allies, tits & penduline tits | work=World Bird List Version 6.1 | url=http://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/waxwings/ | publisher=International Ornithologists' Union| access-date= 15 February 2016 }}</ref>

==Description==
The only pied (black-and-white) tit in India, this species has the wing-coverts, crown, sides of head, chin, throat, a ventral band running down the breast and belly to the vent black. The cheeks below the eye, the ear-coverts and a patch on the nape are white. The wing has white on the outer primaries and the base of the secondaries. The last tertiaries are completely white. The two outer tail feathers are white while the next has the outer web white and the remaining black.<ref name=fbi2>{{cite book|page=79|title= The Fauna of British India, Including Ceylon and Burma. Birds|volume=1| edition=2nd| author=Baker, ECS|url=https://archive.org/stream/birds01bakeiala#page/79/mode/1up/ |publisher=Taylor and Francis, London| year=1924}}</ref><ref name=fbi>{{cite book |page=49 |url= https://archive.org/stream/birdsindia01oaterich#page/49/mode/1up/ |title= The Fauna of British India, Including Ceylon and Burma. Birds| volume=1|  year=1889| author=Oates, EW|publisher= Taylor and Francis, London}}</ref> The white of the flanks can be suffused with yellow.<ref name=hbk>{{cite book|author1=Ali, S  |author2=S D Ripley |name-list-style=amp | title=Handbook of the birds of India and Pakistan|edition=2nd|publisher=Oxford University Press|volume= 9|year= 1998 |pages =175–177|isbn=0-19-562063-1 }}</ref>

==Distribution and habitat==
[[File:ParusNuchalisJerdon.jpg|thumb|left|From Jerdon's ''Illustrations of Indian Ornithology'' (1847)]]
This species was discovered in the Eastern Ghats near [[Nellore]] by [[Thomas C. Jerdon|T C Jerdon]] who received a specimen from a local hunter.<ref>{{cite book|url = https://archive.org/stream/birdsofindiabein21jerd#page/279/mode/1up/|page=279|author=Jerdon, TC|year=1863|title=Birds of India. Volume 2. Part 1|publisher=The Military Orphan Press, Calcutta}}</ref> A specimen was later obtained in 1863 from near Bangalore and for a long time the species was not observed anywhere in southern India. [[Allan Octavian Hume|A O Hume]] had suggested in that the two populations might represent different species.<ref name=fbi2/> The southern population was subsequently noted when [[Salim Ali (ornithologist)|Salim Ali]] collected specimens from the [[Biligirirangan Hills]]. The species occurs in the nearby Kaveri valley area where ''Parus cinereus stupae'' is also found. The species has also been reported from the [[Chittoor]] district of [[Andhra Pradesh]].<ref>{{cite journal| author=Jones, S|year= 2007| title= Sightings of White-naped Tit Parus nuchalis in Arogyavaram, Chittoor district, Andhra Pradesh| journal= Indian Birds|volume=3 | issue = 5 |pages=93–94| url=http://www.indianbirds.in/pdfs/IB.3.5.198-199.pdf}}</ref> Salim Ali had claimed that the two species were mutually exclusive, however there is no support for this.<ref>{{cite journal| author=Lott, E. J.| author2=C. Lott| name-list-style=amp |year= 1999| title= On the occurrence of White-naped Tit ''Parus nuchalis'' in S. India| journal= Forktail |volume=15|pages=93–94| url=http://orientalbirdclub.org/publications/forktail/15pdfs/Lott-Tit.pdf}}</ref><ref name=mysore>{{cite journal|title= Observations on the White-naped Tit ''Parus nuchalis'' in Cauvery Wildlife Sanctuary, Karnataka|author= Sadananda KB|author2= D. H. Tanuja|author3= M. Sahana|author4= T. Girija|author5= A. Sharath|author6= M. K. Vishwanath|author7= A. Shivaprakash|name-list-style= amp|journal=Indian Birds |year=2010| volume=6|issue=1|pages=12–14}}</ref> The distribution in western India is larger and better known, ranging mainly in areas of [[Kutch]] and extending into parts of Rajasthan and Haryana.<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Ahlawat|first1=Rakesh|last2=Sharma|first2=Chetna|last3=Dalal|first3=Sonu|title=White-naped Tit Machlolophus nuchalis in Haryana|url=http://indianbirds.in/pdfs/IB_14_4_AhlawatETAL_WhitenapedTit.pdf|journal=Indian Birds|volume=14|page=125}}</ref> A specimen in the British Museum marked as being from ''Bootan'' (Bhutan) is considered to be in error.<ref name=fbi/><ref>{{cite book|author=Gadow, Hans| url= https://archive.org/stream/catalogueofbirds08brit#page/38/mode/1up/|page=38| title=Catalogue of the birds in the British Museum. Cichlomorphae Part 5. Volume 8|year=1883}}</ref> Records from Wynaad, Anshi National Park and Dharwad have also been considered doubtful.<ref name=mysore/>

==Behaviour and ecology==
These birds are believed to live at very low densities in small numbers. They are shy and are best detected by their calls which have been described as musical whistling notes ''tee-whi-whi'' or ''see pit-pit-pit-pit''.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Hussain, SA |author2=Tiwari, JK |year=1992|title= Status and distribution of White-winged Black Tit in Kachchh, Gujarat India|journal= Bird Conserv. Int.|volume=1992|pages=115–122|doi=10.1017/S0959270900002343 |doi-access=free}}</ref> They forage within well-established territories which pairs will defend from others of their own species. Both males and females make use of roost hollows and individuals have been observed to use the same roost for more than six years. The male of a pair accompanies the female to its roost before proceeds to his own roost site. The birds move their head from side to side in a nearby bush and then fly into the roost cavity, turning around at the entrance so that they can look out and fly if threatened.<ref name=":0" /> The birds feed on insects and the berries of ''Salvadora oleoides''. They may also obtain nectar from the flowers of ''Capparis aphylla'' and will sometimes visit rainwater puddles to drink.<ref name=jkt/> The breeding season in Rajasthan is during the monsoons, from May to August. The nest is a pad of fibre and hair (sometimes plucked from roadkill) placed inside a cavity typically on a tree. They choose natural hollows as well as cavities made by woodpeckers and coppersmith barbets. Nests have been found in old trees of ''Salvadora persica'' and ''Boswellia serrata''.<ref name=skt>{{cite journal|author1=Sharma, S. K. |author2=Koli, V. K. |year=2014| title= Population and nesting characteristics of the Vulnerable White-naped Tit Parus nuchalis at Sajjangarh Wildlife Sanctuary, Rajasthan, India| journal=Forktail |volume=30| pages=1–4}}</ref> The clutch size is not known but adults with three young have been observed. The female develops a brood-patch and it is not known if the male incubates. Males have been seen carrying food to the female at nest.<ref name=":0">{{cite journal |author1=Potter, A. B. |author2=Dhondt, A. A. |year=2019 |title=Behavioural observations on White-naped Tit Machlolophus nuchalis during its breeding season |url=https://indianbirds.in/pdfs/IB_14_6_Potter_Dhondt_WhitenapedTit.pdf |journal=Indian Birds |volume=14 |issue=6 |pages=161–165}}</ref> Both parents take part in care of the chicks.<ref name=hbk/> The chicks are fed mainly with non-hairy caterpillars, the parents may bring food as late as 2000 Hrs in the evening.<ref name=jkt>{{cite journal|author1=Tiwari, J. K. |author2=Rahmani, Asad R. |year=1996| title= The current status and biology of the White-naped Tit ''Parus nuchalis'' in Kutch, Gujarat, India| journal=Forktail |volume=12| pages=79–85}}</ref> In Gujarat it has been said to be dependent on old woodpeckers nest holes, especially those made by [[yellow-crowned woodpecker]]s, which are used both for nesting and roosting.<ref name="pcr">{{cite book|author1=Rasmussen, P.C.  |author2=Anderton, J.C.  |name-list-style=amp |year=2005| title= Birds of South Asia. The Ripley Guide. Volume 2| publisher= Smithsonian Institution and Lynx Edicions| page=528}}</ref><ref name=tba/><ref>{{cite journal|author= Tiwari, J.K. |year=2001| title= Status and distribution of the White-naped Tit ''Parus nuchalis'' in Gujarat and Rajasthan| journal= Journal of the Bombay Natural History Society |volume=98 |issue=1| pages=26–30|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48583235}}</ref> Suggestions that the species might migrate from western to southern India have not found support and birds (including juveniles) have been seen in southern India during summer. Birds ringed in western India have been recaptured within a radius of 5 to 7&nbsp;km. Breeding has not been studied in the southern population.<ref name=mysore/>

This species is said to have undergone a rapid population decline in the recent past. The habitat of dense ''Acacia'' scrub is severely degraded and fragmented in western India especially due to the collection of old branches with potential nest holes for firewood.<ref name=tba>{{cite book |url=http://birdbase.hokkaido-ies.go.jp/rdb/rdb_en/parunuch.pdf |editor=Collar, NJ |editor2=AV Andreev |editor3=S Chan |editor4=MJ Crosby |editor5=S Subramanya |editor6=JA Tobias |year=2001 |title=Threatened Birds of Asia |publisher=BirdLife International |pages=2265–2270 |archive-date=2019-02-02 |access-date=2010-06-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190202021123/http://birdbase.hokkaido-ies.go.jp/rdb/rdb_en/parunuch.pdf }}</ref><ref name=sah>{{cite journal|author=Hussain SA|year=1996| title = The Whitewinged Tit |journal=[[Newsletter for Birdwatchers]] | volume=36| issue=1|pages=18–19|url=https://archive.org/stream/NLBW36_1#page/n17/mode/1up}}</ref>

